Author: cspence
Title: Pomello (YC W15) Is Hiring a Front-End Developer – Build Better Company Cultures
Content:
WHAT IS POMELLO We are passionate about helping companies build a better employee experience. To us, this means understanding and driving authentic company cultures from the ground up to build a great workplace that results in a high performing team. We combine research-backed methodology to capture data about employee values and motivators. We then use this data to create analytics that empower managers and employees to perform better. Pomello is YC-backed and seed-funded.

WHY POMELLO You want to work on a big problem. You are an enthusiastic self starter and want to grow your career and skill-set. You are customer focused and want to see the impact of your work. You want to work on a small team with big ambitions, and have fun while getting good work done.

THE ROLE Frontend Developer and UX/UI Designer--We are looking for a frontend developer with a knack for simple design. You will be responsible for the look and feel of the entire product. We are looking for someone who can balance speed and risk in the development process. Most importantly, you should be able to adapt to changing priorities, and enjoy high levels of autonomy and accountability.

HERE ARE A FEW OF THE THINGS YOU WILL WORK ON Data Visualization--Make predictive analytics easily understandable and actionable. Design of enterprise analytics dashboard and interactions (think mixpanel) Mobile app product extension

REQUIRED SKILLS: Front-end development experience Strong knowledge of HTML/CSS/Javascript/JQuery

BONUS SKILLS: Design/UI/UX work Experience with a modern front-end javascript framework, such as AngularJS Experience with Node.js Experience with responsive web development / optimizing for both desktop and mobile users

rearranged my repo, here is the scalable, pipelined way of doing this, it ends up being an insertion sort with the benefit of small fanout (for lower energy), better scalability (faster due to lower fanout and shorter critical path with pipelining), and maintains O(1) throughput (no fill/drain cycle).

https://github.com/theocean154/dau/blob/master/docs/part_sor...

Author: ygra
Content: The limit is usually address space fragmentation and at one point not being able to find a piece of memory large enough for an allocation. Depending on the allocation patterns this may happen around 3 GiB but for some applications even around 1.7 GiB already. VS gets unbearably slow around 2 GiB memory, though, most likely because the native allocator has to piece together all free pieces of memory again and in the managed part the GC probably has fun trying to compact memory.
